			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I'm going to turn this post into dev corner once I get most mage concerns all typed down. If you believe I have forgotten something or have a comment to make post it please.
<br />

<br />
I noticed lately a lot of mages have gotten concerned with the mage class. Most likely a lot of this swell of concern started with the nerf(Who's name we are not to speak... Well... I will anyway. The Pet Canni Nerf). Mages then found their dps very hampered when they lost their main form of mana regen. I won't go into everything since their has been so much debate about it already. 
<br />

<br />
With a lower dps Mages find themselves in a bad spot. We are no longer one of the top three damage dealers. We have nothing else of real interest to groups. We are no longer able to solo.  
<br />

<br />
I know you Devs rolled your eyes and sighed at that one.
<br />

<br />
Now... Many of these topics are really interwoven together. Mostly being damage and pets. So lets talk about that for now.
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Mage Concern Number 1</span>
<br />

<br />
Nukes. A great portion of Mage dps. Except for the occasional casting of mod rod, this is the one spell catagory that the cost of it matters. Pets/summons/buffs are done during a time where there is plenty of time to med and regroup. Nukes however are during battle where medding is more difficult or in a place where horses are disabled.  This wasn't a problem when Mage mana regen was better, but now it hampers our dps since we are no longer able to consistently keep up our sustained damage. 
<br />

<br />
Perhaps a negative resist? Perhaps cheaper to cast? I know Dev are very hesitant to change our nukes in anyway, but I would hope you would take a look and consider changes to bring our dps more in line with what mages are supposed to be.
<br />

<br />
How about a new t-rod? The t-rod spell would be self targetable only. No drop, but otherwise the same of the original t-rod. It could not be dropped or traded, can be clicked without waiting for a recast. This would help bring up mage dps to what it should be without the fear of unbridled mana regen without consequences.
<br />

<br />
The second issue to nukes is aggro. A lot of mages are having trouble upping their dps simply because they cannot do so without dying. Would there be any way to consider lessening the aggro of mage nukes? 
<br />

<br />
<span style="text-decoration: underline">Summary of Concerns 1:</span>
<br />

<br />
1. Reconsider cost/size of nukes after the loss of Mage's main form of mana regen.
<br />
2. Reconsider the amount of aggro created by Mage nukes.
<br />

<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Mage Concern Number 2</span>
<br />

<br />
Besides Nukes, Mages are characterized by one other thing. Of course that is the Pet.
<br />

<br />
This is really where the concern over Mage soloing becomes an issue for many mages. I assume the Devs realize that Mages have been a solo class for almost all of their careers. From level 1 to about lvl 59/60 we can solo for decent exp since our pet could in some way hold its own. It didn't matter if 1 pet could take the mob or we were forced to chain cast pets to do it. When we wanted to group, we could group. When we wanted to solo, we could solo. Our pets were there to help in either case.
<br />

<br />
Up until the recent surge in Mob dps, *Planes of Power* , Mages could solo at their choice. Now, it might not have been preferable to grouping, but the choice remained. But now that choice is gone.
<br />

<br />
<span style="text-decoration: underline">The Devs have changed a fundamental characteristic of a Class.</span>
<br />

<br />
I would really like the Devs to recognize this and to tell Mages what their position is on the issue of mage soloing. 
<br />

<br />
Have you(the devs) decided to officially change an entire class that has been based on its ability to solo for so long? It states on the Everquest homepage that one of the premises of the class is to solo.
<br />

<br />
If so, what is the compensation for this? Higher pet dps? Better innate stats? Some other upgrade?
<br />

<br />
I would wish you would make a statement about this to the mage class or change your sites to describe Magicians as a non-solo class. It really is ironic to read Mages can solo on EQ homepage, but find myself killed in less than 30 seconds to any exp mob.
<br />

<br />

<br />

<br />
Also another concern of mages about pets is basically the fire pet. We know it doesn't work. You must know it doesn't work. No mage uses except for just the occasional fun of seeing Ice Comet or maybe a duel. Just make it cast a nuke, make it cast that in a reliable fashion(Unlike SoR aa ability which still doesn't nuke reliably I think.). If you were forced to give us a pet only kei to make it even cast its spells, doesn't that say the pet still needs work?
<br />

<br />
On the subject of the Fire pet... There are many great ideas on it. Instead of a Wizard, make the fire pet a Mage caster. Maybe it casts Malosinia(or other debuff), casts fire nuke, casts magic nuke... And thats about it. Doesn't need to cast anything else. 
<br />

<br />
The ae spells of the pet now make it too dangerous to use. Its mana pool is far to short lived. I don't need a fire pet to stun really(Thought the idea of the constant stunning fire pets is a nice idea). I don't need it to do anything but nuke. 
<br />

<br />
Make it nuke. Make it do it constantly. Make its mana pool larger(or just so large we don't worry about it ever going lom). Make it a Mage caster.
<br />

<br />
Now onto the less urgent pet fix. The Earth Pet. Mages don't need root(except for the few yo yo kiters) and many consider it annoying that the root alone prevents the pets use in groups. Since Mages cannot not solo once they acquire the pet, the pet has no other purpose and it is put in the back of the spell book. Remove the root and replace it with a snare possibly? That would be a great help to this pet.
<br />

<br />
<span style="text-decoration: underline">Summary of Concern's 2:</span>
<br />

<br />
1. Pet Survivability.
<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">2. A statement on Mage Soloing.</span>
<br />
3. Fix Fire pet for good.
<br />
4. Replace Earth pet's root with snare or some other spell.
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Mage Concern Number 3</span>
<br />

<br />
Utility for raids. Mage utility for raids are pretty much non existent except for 2 spells. T-rods and Coth.
<br />

<br />
One of these spells is the most "banned from zone" spell in the ENTIRE game.
<br />

<br />
So half of mage usefullness is now eliminated from raid encounters.
<br />

<br />
So how many mages does it take to get a raid full of mod rods? Just one.
<br />

<br />
And the larger problem is that if that one mage was not there? No problem. Just get a wizard. They have higher dps anyway. Rogue for the same reason. A Druid! for the same reason. A priest class can nuke as well as us when they want to.  
<br />

<br />
I know the Devs are interested in Mages being more useful in raids, considering that the recent changes made to MSIV were made in this regard. But what do we bring? Even with a tough pet? Also an additional problem with the raid centered pet is that many Raid Leaders still have issues with pets, often calling for "Lose Pets!" on bad push situations.
<br />

<br />
My suggestion is to allow coth in all zones.
<br />

<br />
I know that sounds bad, but let me explain my point of view.
<br />

<br />
You said yourselves that coth was meant to bring in stragglers. Why not create a new coth, of the same level as the last, that has a 1 minute refresh time?
<br />

<br />
This prevents cothing an entire raid to a spot since at best it would take 71 minutes to coth a raid to any given spot.... And if the mage didn't die in the process... And totally negating mana for the spell...And that the group was filled with new people as soon as the last left... And assumming the mage can insta-click the spell gem every single time. 
<br />

<br />

<br />

<br />
Utility part two consists primarily of Mages summoning items.
<br />

<br />
Besides the t-rods stated above Mages summon a haste mask, three good pet weapons, and focus items to give to lower level players.
<br />

<br />
Summoned focus items have gotten less useful as time goes along for the reason that better focus equipment continues to drop. The only times I am ever asked for focus items is from characters under level 59.
<br />

<br />
Probably the annoyance of summoned items with Mages is that we are called the "summoning" class a lot, but besides for t-rods there is nothing really outstanding in this regard. Mages mostly get "trinket" summoning spells. In addition to this several mages have pointed out how other classes outstrip Mages in the summoning department. The first thing to come to mind is the Cleric summoned Proc hammer. 
<br />

<br />
I remember when the cleric proc hammer was first created and I would see every cleric and their brother meleeing the mob. This really annoyed mages that another class suddenly was better than us at summoning. 
<br />

<br />
I would love to see a continuance of the present summoned pet weapons. Maybe a better haste mask? <img src="images/smiles/icon_smile.gif" alt="Smile" border="0" /> Of course that would mean a removal of the current pet haste cap. Though I would still be happy to see new summoned weapons with special effects on them. 
<br />

<br />
Instead of a pet that casts a snare, why not a weapon that occasionally procs it? Or maybe a weapon that procs a debuff? There are many effects that can be put onto pet only weapons.
<br />

<br />
<span style="text-decoration: underline">Summary of Concern 3:</span>
<br />

<br />
1. Utility. Mages really have little to none for raids. 
<br />
2. Utility concerning summoned items.
<br />

<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Mage Concern Number 4</span>
<br />

<br />
Defensive spells. Up until PoP it has been understood that with pets that could stand up to a mob one on one, it would be over powering to have defensive spells. It was said by SOE that we give up all defensive power to be strong offensively, but this is not true anymore.
<br />

<br />
After PoP our pets have no chance of standing up to an exp mob and we are alone among casting classes because we have no defensive spell, besides gate.
<br />

<br />
Is it possible now to give the mage class defensive spells that could make up for the loss of solo power?
<br />

<br />
There are many ideas on the Mage boards for this. Continue with the pet summoned weapons line, by giving us new ones that can do nice procs. How about a weapon to procs stun? A weapon that procs snare? A weapon that procs even some form of slow(I do know that it is unlikely you will ever do this, but this is how much Mages valued soloing.)? 
<br />

<br />
Or how about just giving us the spells themselves? Even a summoned item that we must right click to do that spell?
<br />

<br />
Many mages would like the Devs to make a statement on this as well. Has it gotten to the point that since Mages are no longer powerful compared to the mobs, that we can get defensive spells to help us?
<br />

<br />
<span style="text-decoration: underline">Summary of Mage Concerns 4:</span>
<br />

<br />
1. Since Mages are weaker after Pop, could we acquire defensive spells(Snare, Root, or even slow)?
<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">2. Make a statement on the likelyhood of this occuring.</span>
<br />

<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Most Important Points of this Article:</span>
<br />

<br />
If anything is done among the things listed in this article, please respond to these first before anything else.
<br />

<br />
1. Make a Statement on Mage Soloing. Something solid rather than a general answer of "We will look into it."
<br />
2. Make a Statement concerning the Mage class acquiring defensive spells. Many mages are asking this as an answer to our problems and an answer to its likelyhood would be appreciated.
<br />

<br />

<br />
Thank you for taking the time to read this. If any mages have anything to add to this, please do.   <span style="text-decoration: underline"></span> <span style="font-weight: bold"></span>  <span style="font-weight: bold"></span></span><span class="gensmall"><br /><br />Last edited by Yawgmoth on Mon Feb 09, 2004 11:27 pm; edited 7 times in total</span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
